Following is the solution to my own question. It took me a while to figure out. 
P.S. I&#39;ve developed the solution ignoring any possibility of pallindromes.

    import java.util.*;

    class WOG{
	
	static int m = 0;
	static int n = 0;
	static int[] x = {0,-1,0,1};
	static int[] y = {-1,0,1,0};
	
	public static int func(char[][] grid, int row, int col, String word, int k, int[][]g2){
	
	int occ = 0;
	
	if(row&gt;=m || row&lt;0 || col&lt;0 || col&gt;=n)
		return 0;
	
	if(grid[row][col]!=word.charAt(k))
		return 0;
		
	if(k==word.length()-1)
		return 1;

	if(g2[row][col]==0)
		return 0;

	g2[row][col] = 0;

	for(int dir=0;dir&lt;4;dir++){

		int rd = row+x[dir];
		int cd = col+y[dir];

		
		occ += func(grid,rd,cd,word,k+1,g2);
	}

	return occ;

	}

	public static int pattern(char[][] grid, String word){
	
	int res = 0;

	int[][] g2 = new int[m][n];
	for(int i=0;i&lt;m;i++){
		for(int j=0;j&lt;n;j++){
			g2[i][j]=-1;
		}
	}
	
	for(int i=0;i&lt;m;i++){
		for(int j=0;j&lt;n;j++){
			res += func(grid,i,j,word,0,g2);
		}
	}

	return res;
	
	}

	public static void main(String[] args){
		
		char[][] grid2 = {{&#39;m&#39;,&#39;o&#39;,&#39;b&#39;,&#39;s&#39;,&#39;n&#39;},
				  {&#39;m&#39;,&#39;o&#39;,&#39;i&#39;,&#39;l&#39;,&#39;e&#39;},
			 	  {&#39;m&#39;,&#39;b&#39;,&#39;i&#39;,&#39;l&#39;,&#39;e&#39;},
				  {&#39;o&#39;,&#39;b&#39;,&#39;i&#39;,&#39;l&#39;,&#39;e&#39;}};

		char[][] grid = {{&#39;c&#39;,&#39;a&#39;,&#39;r&#39;},
				 {&#39;a&#39;,&#39;r&#39;,&#39;c&#39;},
			 	 {&#39;c&#39;,&#39;r&#39;,&#39;a&#39;}};

		char[][] grid3 = {{&#39;b&#39;,&#39;a&#39;},
				  {&#39;y&#39;,&#39;c&#39;}};

		m = 2;
		n = 2;
		int ans = pattern(grid3,&quot;baby&quot;);
		System.out.println(ans);
	}
    }
		

I&#39;ve made use of recursion and backtracking. 
Edit : I&#39;ve placed a new 2x2 grid g2, which acts as a visit verifier. If for a word, a character has already been visited in the grid, it won&#39;t be visited again. So, this solves the problem of pallindromes.

