you can replace a value in an array with `array[0] = &quot;XX&quot;`. So in your case it would be `card2[r][c] = &quot;XX&quot;`.

To be sure every number is used one time an easy solution would be an ArrayList. So you can use it like

    List&lt;Integer&gt; usedNumbers = new ArrayList&lt;Integer&gt;();
    
    //  when number was used
    usedNumbers.add(call);
    
    //check if already used
    boolean alreadyUsed = usedNumbers.contains(call);

Another tip:
```java
for (r = 0; r &lt; card2.length; r++) {
    for(c = 0; c &lt; card2.length; c++) {
       ...
    }
}

```

only works if the number of arrays in `card2` equals the number of items in each list. If not you will get an `OutOfBoundsException`. 
The correct way is to use the length of the inner array for `c`:

